<i>[fire crackles]</i>

00:04.254 --> 00:07.257
<i>[building ambient music]</i>

00:07.257 --> 00:14.223
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:14.223 --> 00:16.016
<i>[rock music]</i>

00:16.016 --> 00:18.268
<i>- Here in The Forge</i>
<i>we have a taste for history.</i>

00:18.268 --> 00:20.604
- That's right, baby,
"Forged in Fire."

00:20.604 --> 00:23.524
<i>- But this time, we're</i>
<i>tackling fictional weapons</i>

00:23.524 --> 00:25.192
<i>inspired by history.</i>

00:25.192 --> 00:26.818
What a great knife movie.

00:26.818 --> 00:30.656
Tonight, we pay a little
tribute to Tinseltown.

00:30.656 --> 00:32.616
<i>It's the Hollywood edition.</i>

00:32.616 --> 00:35.285
- Brian, get to the chopper.

00:35.285 --> 00:38.372
<i>- Four bladesmiths,</i>
<i>three rounds,</i>

00:38.372 --> 00:42.042
<i>two finalists,</i>
<i>one goal.</i>

00:42.042 --> 00:44.127
<i>- I love this competition.</i>

00:44.127 --> 00:46.380
<i>[music slows]</i>

00:46.380 --> 00:48.131
- Did you bring enough
for everyone?

00:48.131 --> 00:49.591
- Oh.

00:49.591 --> 00:51.134
<i>- Which smith will</i>
<i>earn the role</i>

00:51.134 --> 00:54.096
<i>of "Forged in Fire" champion?</i>

00:54.096 --> 01:00.936
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:00.936 --> 01:02.854
<i>[tense music]</i>

01:02.854 --> 01:04.773
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:04.773 --> 01:07.359
<i>- My name is Brian Bivens.</i>
<i>During the day I work</i>

01:07.359 --> 01:09.695
as a project manager
for a financial firm.

01:09.695 --> 01:12.364
<i>And obviously</i>
<i>it's a very safe environment.</i>

01:12.364 --> 01:15.367
So it's nice having
this outlet where everything

01:15.367 --> 01:18.036
is extremely dangerous
and hazardous.

01:18.036 --> 01:20.163
<i>- My name's Trystan Nguyen.</i>
<i>I'm 19.</i>

01:20.163 --> 01:21.748
On a typical day
in Trystan land

01:21.748 --> 01:23.125
I work in a pizza shop

01:23.125 --> 01:25.836
<i>and I'm studying to be a chef.</i>

01:25.836 --> 01:28.130
<i>I kind of pull my inspiration</i>
<i>from everything around me.</i>

01:28.130 --> 01:29.840
If I see something in
a video game

01:29.840 --> 01:32.467
that I really like, I'll try
to make it in real life.

01:32.467 --> 01:35.345
- My name is Mike Deibert.
I am a journeyman bladesmith

01:35.345 --> 01:37.222
<i>and an elementary school</i>
<i>teacher.</i>

01:37.222 --> 01:39.308
I teach Spanish and reading.

01:39.308 --> 01:41.351
<i>There's a lot of love</i>
<i>I pour into it,</i>

01:41.351 --> 01:43.312
but that two months
in the summertime,

01:43.312 --> 01:46.523
bladesmithing
is a really good therapy.

01:46.523 --> 01:48.859
- My name is Doug Loving.
I am a sergeant

01:48.859 --> 01:50.527
for the Arizona Department
of Corrections.

01:50.527 --> 01:53.989
I have 4 four kids.
15, 12, 3, and 1.

01:53.989 --> 01:56.783
<i>My wife said, "You can go to</i>
<i>'Forged in Fire,'</i>

01:56.783 --> 02:00.203
but you better make sure
you bring back some money."

02:00.203 --> 02:02.331
Winning for me would mean
I can come home.

02:02.331 --> 02:03.749
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:03.749 --> 02:06.585
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

02:06.585 --> 02:08.837
You're here for a competition
in three rounds

02:08.837 --> 02:10.630
designed to test every aspect

02:10.630 --> 02:12.466
of your bladesmithing
capabilities

02:12.466 --> 02:15.552
all in front of a panel of
expert judges who will decide

02:15.552 --> 02:18.055
which of you is our next
"Forged in Fire" champion,

02:18.055 --> 02:20.891
walking out of here with
a check for $10,000.

02:20.891 --> 02:22.559
Let's meet your judges now.

02:22.559 --> 02:24.478
- Up first, two-time
"Forged in Fire" champion,

02:24.478 --> 02:26.188
Ben Abbott.

02:26.188 --> 02:29.232
Historic weapons re-creation
specialist, David Baker.

02:29.232 --> 02:32.277
And last, edged weapons
specialist, Doug Marcaida.

02:32.277 --> 02:33.987
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:33.987 --> 02:36.907
Bladesmiths, today we pay
a little tribute

02:36.907 --> 02:38.825
to Tinseltown.

02:38.825 --> 02:42.454
La La Land.
Better known as Hollywood.

02:42.454 --> 02:45.624
Movies such as "Zorro,"
"The Expendables,"

02:45.624 --> 02:47.709
and "The Hunted" have featured
not only

02:47.709 --> 02:49.628
the work of great knifemakers,

02:49.628 --> 02:52.881
but have also inspired others
to engage in the craft.

02:52.881 --> 02:56.009
Which of you has been inspired
by a movie or film?

02:56.009 --> 02:58.053
- "Conan."
- "Lord of the Rings."

02:58.053 --> 03:00.180
- Well, gentlemen,
in keeping with that theme,

03:00.180 --> 03:02.557
today you will not be making
signature blades

03:02.557 --> 03:04.309
in your signature style.

03:04.309 --> 03:05.811
Instead, we'll be giving you

03:05.811 --> 03:08.647
an 8-inch piece
of W1 round stock

03:08.647 --> 03:10.649
from which to forge this.

03:10.649 --> 03:13.568
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:13.568 --> 03:15.153
The "Rambo" survival knife.

03:15.153 --> 03:18.073
Similar to Vietnam-era
pilot survival knives,

03:18.073 --> 03:19.866
John Rambo's weapon of choice

03:19.866 --> 03:21.535
was introduced to audiences
around the world

03:21.535 --> 03:25.080
in the 1982 Hollywood classic
"First Blood."

03:25.080 --> 03:27.290
- Course it's Rambo's knife,
you know.

03:27.290 --> 03:29.751
Thinking of Hollywood blades
that would inspire.

03:29.751 --> 03:31.294
<i>It's beautiful.</i>

03:31.294 --> 03:33.505
- We'd like you to keep
that film in mind

03:33.505 --> 03:36.216
as you design and forge
your survival knives

03:36.216 --> 03:38.218
within the following
parameters.

03:38.218 --> 03:41.388
<i>The length of your blades must</i>
<i>be between 12 and 15 inches.</i>

03:41.388 --> 03:43.682
<i>Your blades must be at least</i>
<i>two inches wide.</i>

03:43.682 --> 03:45.392
<i>You must feature</i>
<i>a clipped point,</i>

03:45.392 --> 03:47.352
<i>decorative file work</i>
<i>on the spine,</i>

03:47.352 --> 03:49.771
<i>as well as a through tang.</i>

03:49.771 --> 03:51.940
In the second round,
you'll attach handles

03:51.940 --> 03:53.316
to those blades,
turning them into

03:53.316 --> 03:54.985
fully functioning
survival knives

03:54.985 --> 03:56.987
that will be tested
for tip retention

03:56.987 --> 04:00.574
and overall strength in
a spike chop

04:00.574 --> 04:05.162
and for edge retention in
a tarp and rope slice.

04:05.162 --> 04:07.497
You will have ten minutes
to design your blades.

04:07.497 --> 04:09.791
You will have three hours
in which to forge them.

04:09.791 --> 04:11.293
Good luck, bladesmiths.

04:11.293 --> 04:14.671
Your fight for survival
starts... now.

04:14.671 --> 04:16.506
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:16.506 --> 04:18.341
Let me ask you this:
survival knife,

04:18.341 --> 04:19.926
what does it mean to you?

04:19.926 --> 04:21.887
- I would go with a really
tough temper on it

04:21.887 --> 04:23.972
because you want to be able
to baton it through logs.

04:23.972 --> 04:25.223
You want to be able
to chop on things,

04:25.223 --> 04:27.017
but at the same time,

04:27.017 --> 04:28.435
you want to be able
to cut your dinner, you know,

04:28.435 --> 04:29.644
if you're lucky
enough to find some.

04:29.644 --> 04:31.480
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:31.480 --> 04:33.356
<i>- I went to see the movie</i>
<i>"Rambo" when I was a kid</i>

04:33.356 --> 04:35.484
<i>in the movie theater,</i>
<i>and I remember</i>

04:35.484 --> 04:37.235
<i>thinking how cool this was.</i>

04:37.235 --> 04:38.820
It's something that
if this guy's gonna use it,

04:38.820 --> 04:40.655
it's gonna save his life.

04:40.655 --> 04:43.116
<i>I'm kind of designing this</i>
<i>knife after a Bowie knife.</i>

04:43.116 --> 04:44.910
<i>I'll probably have</i>
<i>a little more curves in it</i>

04:44.910 --> 04:47.204
than a Bowie knife,
but I feel comfortable with it,

04:47.204 --> 04:48.747
so I'm going with that.

04:48.747 --> 04:50.457
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:50.457 --> 04:52.876
- Anybody out there ever been
in a survival situation?

04:52.876 --> 04:55.921
- Yeah, I was in high school.
- [laughing]

04:55.921 --> 04:59.382
- So I've seen "Rambo," like,
definitely a couple of times,

04:59.382 --> 05:01.635
but I make blades mostly from,
like, video games

05:01.635 --> 05:03.804
and things
'cause I'm kind of nerdy.

05:03.804 --> 05:05.680
<i>So my knife,</i>
<i>it's gotta have a clip point.</i>

05:05.680 --> 05:07.432
<i>And as far as the guard goes,</i>

05:07.432 --> 05:09.643
<i>I kind of want it to be,</i>
<i>like, kind of swirled.</i>

05:09.643 --> 05:12.562
'Cause that's kind of
blacksmithy.

05:12.562 --> 05:14.064
- I like it.

05:14.064 --> 05:16.441
The survival knife
is something

05:16.441 --> 05:19.861
that every outdoorsman
is very familiar with.

05:19.861 --> 05:22.697
<i>I make outdoor blades,</i>
<i>things that are meant</i>

05:22.697 --> 05:26.117
to be used, beat on,
treated very roughly.

05:26.117 --> 05:28.495
<i>I started making knives</i>
<i>because my brother</i>

05:28.495 --> 05:31.540
was in a paralyzing
motorcycle accident.

05:31.540 --> 05:33.625
<i>Learning about making blades</i>
<i>with him</i>

05:33.625 --> 05:35.001
<i>was something that</i>
<i>motivated him,</i>

05:35.001 --> 05:36.378
<i>helped him get up</i>
<i>and get moving.</i>

05:36.378 --> 05:39.172
It's been an amazing ride.

05:39.172 --> 05:41.216
- I feel like I'm drawing
with a big, giant crayon.

05:41.216 --> 05:42.884
[laughs]

05:42.884 --> 05:45.846
<i>To date, I have not made</i>
<i>a knife from a movie.</i>

05:45.846 --> 05:48.306
So this is a first for me,
and I'm gonna draw just

05:48.306 --> 05:50.058
a general idea of what I want.

05:50.058 --> 05:52.310
And then we will hopefully get
somewhere close to it.

05:52.310 --> 05:54.896
<i>Everybody back home</i>
<i>is rooting for me.</i>

05:54.896 --> 05:56.982
<i>They either think it's gonna</i>
<i>be a beautiful train wreck</i>

05:56.982 --> 05:58.567
<i>or a beautiful piece of work.</i>

05:58.567 --> 06:00.944
So either way,
they're gonna be satisfied.

06:00.944 --> 06:02.946
- Bladesmiths,
your design period is closed.

06:02.946 --> 06:05.448
Your three hour forge time
starts...

06:05.448 --> 06:07.284
now.

06:07.284 --> 06:10.203
We got four smiths heading
in four different directions.

06:10.203 --> 06:11.830
- Welding!
- Welding.

06:11.830 --> 06:13.665
- Everybody's welding.

06:13.665 --> 06:16.793
<i>- My initial thought is</i>
<i>to weld a handle on the steel.</i>

06:16.793 --> 06:19.588
That's gonna give me
the best access to The Forge,

06:19.588 --> 06:21.715
and then working on
the different machines

06:21.715 --> 06:24.759
<i>I don't typically use welders</i>
<i>that often,</i>

06:24.759 --> 06:28.430
and I cannot get this thing
to even spark up.

06:28.430 --> 06:30.724
<i>Fortunately these guys,</i>
<i>they're terrific.</i>

06:30.724 --> 06:32.475
- Get your ground.
- Huh?

06:32.475 --> 06:34.644
- Get your ground on there.
- I'm pushing down.

06:34.644 --> 06:36.646
- No, your ground. Here.
- Oh, this.

06:36.646 --> 06:38.273
- Yeah, there.
- Oh, thank you.

06:38.273 --> 06:39.900
To me, this competition
is all about

06:39.900 --> 06:42.694
improvising, adapting.
Nothing works the way

06:42.694 --> 06:44.404
that you think it's gonna work,
so you gotta

06:44.404 --> 06:46.573
just constantly work through.

06:46.573 --> 06:48.199
- Ah, see, Brian,

06:48.199 --> 06:50.410
his work stick just started
to break off.

06:50.410 --> 06:52.621
<i>- The handle I welded on,</i>
<i>it came off.</i>

06:52.621 --> 06:55.457
So to me it was worth it
to just grab the tongs

06:55.457 --> 06:57.500
to go and see if
that would work for me.

06:57.500 --> 07:00.003
If I'm having trouble,
I'll weld another part on.

07:00.003 --> 07:01.713
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:01.713 --> 07:04.132
<i>- Well, Doug went for</i>
<i>the tongs approach.</i>

07:04.132 --> 07:05.717
Dave, what do you think
about that?

07:05.717 --> 07:07.093
- It's gonna be hard to work

07:07.093 --> 07:08.637
that whole bar
with a pair of tongs.

07:08.637 --> 07:10.513
- The fact that I don't know
how to weld,

07:10.513 --> 07:13.016
<i>I'm not going to risk</i>
<i>screwing up</i>

07:13.016 --> 07:14.309
<i>and wasting precious time.</i>

07:14.309 --> 07:15.727
Hot steel!

07:15.727 --> 07:17.270
I've never used
a power hammer.

07:17.270 --> 07:19.981
<i>So this is gonna be</i>
<i>really fun.</i>

07:19.981 --> 07:21.816
- See Doug?
He's got steel

07:21.816 --> 07:23.610
flipping right out
of Big Blue.

07:23.610 --> 07:26.863
All that time that he's saved
by not welding,

07:26.863 --> 07:29.616
he's losing by having to
recover his steel all the time.

07:29.616 --> 07:31.743
- He's gripping
the sides of the steel,

07:31.743 --> 07:33.787
and Blue will take
that right out of your hand.

07:33.787 --> 07:35.455
<i>- Right now, it looks like</i>
<i>I'm a little behind</i>

07:35.455 --> 07:38.249
where I'd like to be,
but I'll get it caught up.

07:38.249 --> 07:40.960
- It's pretty hard to do lines
from "Rambo."

07:40.960 --> 07:43.213
I think he said,
"You started this. Not me."

07:43.213 --> 07:44.714
Think that's most
of his dialogue.

07:44.714 --> 07:46.132
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:46.132 --> 07:47.676
<i>- I'm getting things going,</i>

07:47.676 --> 07:51.054
but it feels like
it's taking a long time.

07:51.054 --> 07:53.765
What's that saying?
A watched pot never boils?

07:53.765 --> 07:55.600
- Yeah, but you can't help
but watch it.

07:55.600 --> 07:58.103
- That piece of steel is heavy.
- Yeah.

07:58.103 --> 08:01.648
- Do you, right off the bat,
cut it in half

08:01.648 --> 08:03.441
to make your billet,
or do you draw your billet

08:03.441 --> 08:04.818
and then cut it?

08:04.818 --> 08:06.319
- Knowing the size
of the knife

08:06.319 --> 08:08.113
and having eight inches
of that material,

08:08.113 --> 08:10.198
I'd cut three off.
- Right off the bat?

08:10.198 --> 08:11.783
- Oh yeah.
- Right?

08:11.783 --> 08:13.535
- Come on. Come on. Come on.

08:13.535 --> 08:16.663
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:16.663 --> 08:19.290
<i>- Big Blue's kind of just</i>
<i>a dream to work with.</i>

08:19.290 --> 08:20.917
It's not really
throwing around my steel

08:20.917 --> 08:23.670
and it's hammering it out like
I thought it would.

08:23.670 --> 08:26.005
- Trystan, doing
a pretty good job.

08:26.005 --> 08:27.841
It looks like he's got
his drawing over

08:27.841 --> 08:29.509
at his workstation as well.

08:29.509 --> 08:31.594
Wonder if he's re-drawing

08:31.594 --> 08:34.139
his diagram onto
his workstation.

08:34.139 --> 08:35.932
- Parameters,
write those parameters down

08:35.932 --> 08:38.351
where you're gonna see them
again and again and again.

08:38.351 --> 08:39.769
<i>- I'm definitely nervous,</i>
<i>but I know</i>

08:39.769 --> 08:41.563
that I've done things
like this before.

08:41.563 --> 08:43.732
<i>I just gotta not let my mind</i>
<i>get to me on this.</i>

08:43.732 --> 08:45.108
Hot across.

08:45.108 --> 08:47.027
I'm gonna be measuring
right here.

08:47.027 --> 08:49.738
- Bladesmiths, one hour
has elapsed.

08:49.738 --> 08:53.700
You have just two hours
remaining to finish your work.

08:53.700 --> 08:55.869
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:55.869 --> 08:59.456
<i>- So as I start hammering on</i>
<i>this W1 steel, I notice</i>

08:59.456 --> 09:02.459
<i>it's not moving as quickly</i>
<i>as I'd like it to.</i>

09:02.459 --> 09:05.211
<i>So in my mind, hey,</i>
<i>let's hit it harder.</i>

09:05.211 --> 09:06.588
- There you go.

09:06.588 --> 09:08.465
So Brian's got more heat on
his billet now.

09:08.465 --> 09:10.216
He's moving metal faster.

09:10.216 --> 09:12.594
It's what we always say:
the heat is a tool.

09:12.594 --> 09:14.012
Let it do its job.

09:14.012 --> 09:15.597
- There you go.

09:15.597 --> 09:17.307
- When the hot metal drops
towards your crotch,

09:17.307 --> 09:19.851
it's never a good thing.

09:19.851 --> 09:22.812
- Nope, I'm losing it again.

09:22.812 --> 09:25.899
- We've got Doug over here.
- That is too heavy a hammer.

09:25.899 --> 09:27.525
- I use the eight-pound hammer

09:27.525 --> 09:29.903
when I needed to get metal
moved really quick

09:29.903 --> 09:31.780
in a short amount of time.

09:31.780 --> 09:33.281
- Whoa.

09:33.281 --> 09:36.242
Doug is a little bit
red in the face over there.

09:36.242 --> 09:38.536
I mean,
let's keep an eye on him.

09:38.536 --> 09:40.413
<i>- I'm starting to feel</i>
<i>the affects of the heat.</i>

09:40.413 --> 09:43.875
<i>I can feel my--my--my</i>
<i>heart racing a little bit.</i>

09:43.875 --> 09:46.461
I'm going to have to make some
adjustments here.

09:46.461 --> 09:48.755
<i>I'm gonna move over</i>
<i>to the grinder</i>

09:48.755 --> 09:50.131
and finish out what I need
to do over there.

09:50.131 --> 09:51.633
It's not as hot.

09:51.633 --> 09:53.259
<i>I don't want to come on</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire"</i>

09:53.259 --> 09:55.178
and grind out my knife,

09:55.178 --> 09:57.388
but at the time, I don't want
to come on "Forged in Fire"

09:57.388 --> 09:59.808
and have to leave because
I'm becoming a casualty.

09:59.808 --> 10:01.684
So I'm gonna have
to trade off

10:01.684 --> 10:03.311
<i>the lesser</i>
<i>of the two evils here.</i>

10:03.311 --> 10:08.525
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:08.525 --> 10:12.195
- Forging to me is the beauty
of knifemaking.

10:12.195 --> 10:15.740
And once I see this blade
take shape,

10:15.740 --> 10:17.909
I just go at it
and I know exactly what to do

10:17.909 --> 10:19.869
and I'm very, very, comfortable
doing it.

10:19.869 --> 10:21.538
- Mike's doing a fantastic job.

10:21.538 --> 10:23.665
He's moving around this forge
like he owns it.

10:23.665 --> 10:25.583
- Yeah.

10:25.583 --> 10:27.293
- Once I get my blade roughly
to shape,

10:27.293 --> 10:29.295
<i>I realize I have</i>
<i>too much steel.</i>

10:29.295 --> 10:31.798
I need to set aside
a certain amount of time

10:31.798 --> 10:33.591
so I can use it wisely.

10:33.591 --> 10:37.637
- Bladesmiths, you have just
60 minutes remaining

10:37.637 --> 10:39.722
to finish your blades.

10:39.722 --> 10:41.641
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:41.641 --> 10:43.309
<i>- After I get the basic shape</i>
<i>that I need</i>

10:43.309 --> 10:45.687
for the knife itself,
I take it over to the vice

10:45.687 --> 10:47.355
and go grab an angle grinder

10:47.355 --> 10:49.357
<i>because I want to make</i>
<i>an integral guard.</i>

10:49.357 --> 10:52.735
So I need to get these flaps
that I cut in flared out

10:52.735 --> 10:55.905
so that I can start shaping
them how I want them.

10:55.905 --> 10:57.407
This is called
an integral guard

10:57.407 --> 10:58.449
and that means that it's a part

10:58.449 --> 11:00.160
of the billet as a whole.

11:00.160 --> 11:02.036
It has a lot less of a chance
of, like, slipping around

11:02.036 --> 11:03.663
'cause it's, like, attached.

11:03.663 --> 11:05.748
- I really want to talk about
what Trystan is doing

11:05.748 --> 11:07.458
with this integral guard.

11:07.458 --> 11:09.419
- The problem with that is,

11:09.419 --> 11:11.129
it works fine with
a full-tang handle.

11:11.129 --> 11:12.839
Without a full tang,

11:12.839 --> 11:15.216
you've pushed up these
two guard pieces,

11:15.216 --> 11:18.178
but now your handle material's
wider than your guard.

11:18.178 --> 11:20.096
Without that full tang,
there's nothing

11:20.096 --> 11:21.723
to support the sides
of the handle.

11:21.723 --> 11:23.141
- I understand.

11:23.141 --> 11:24.684
- My biggest concerns
right now are that

11:24.684 --> 11:25.935
something's going wrong
with the knife

11:25.935 --> 11:28.146
and that I smell bad.

11:28.146 --> 11:29.898
<i>- I got my file work going.</i>

11:29.898 --> 11:32.609
I got my, the three inches
and a little bit more,

11:32.609 --> 11:34.235
just in case, marked off

11:34.235 --> 11:35.570
and I'm gonna work towards
the middle.

11:35.570 --> 11:37.238
The framework's
a big deal to me

11:37.238 --> 11:38.865
<i>and it kills you to see</i>
<i>contestants go home</i>

11:38.865 --> 11:40.867
<i>because they don't</i>
<i>do their framework.</i>

11:40.867 --> 11:43.369
<i>So I'm gonna learn from</i>
<i>the guys who came before me,</i>

11:43.369 --> 11:45.246
their mistakes,
and I'm gonna make sure

11:45.246 --> 11:46.789
that I'm gonna prepare myself.

11:46.789 --> 11:48.333
All right, little big guy.

11:48.333 --> 11:50.043
And while the blade's
getting hot,

11:50.043 --> 11:51.794
I'm gonna go over
to the scrap pile

11:51.794 --> 11:53.546
<i>and get me couple of pieces</i>
<i>of angle iron.</i>

11:53.546 --> 11:55.965
<i>No need to risk warps,</i>
<i>so my blade</i>

11:55.965 --> 11:57.217
is gonna be nice and straight.

11:57.217 --> 11:58.968
- Doug did something
interesting.

11:58.968 --> 12:01.471
He's got two piece of angle
iron in a vice right here

12:01.471 --> 12:03.932
in anticipation for a warp.

12:03.932 --> 12:05.350
<i>If nothing else,</i>
<i>I'm gonna present</i>

12:05.350 --> 12:07.101
<i>a straight knife</i>
<i>to the judges.</i>

12:07.101 --> 12:09.270
- Whoa, that was a hot blade

12:09.270 --> 12:11.439
that Doug just put in
his quench.

12:11.439 --> 12:15.485
Did you see the core of that
was still red hot?

12:15.485 --> 12:17.320
- [groans]

12:17.320 --> 12:19.364
That's it.

12:19.364 --> 12:21.616
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:21.616 --> 12:23.576
- I have a relatively
straight blade.

12:23.576 --> 12:25.954
I've met all these parameters

12:25.954 --> 12:27.789
<i>so I'm pretty confident.</i>

12:27.789 --> 12:30.541
- Brian is going for
a quench, it looks like.

12:30.541 --> 12:33.753
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:33.753 --> 12:35.129
<i>- I'm just stirring it around,</i>

12:35.129 --> 12:38.341
using these tongs
that I'm not used to.

12:38.341 --> 12:41.010
<i>And sure enough...</i>

12:41.010 --> 12:42.929
[bleep].

12:42.929 --> 12:45.765
- Brian just sent his blade to
the bottom of the quench tank.

12:45.765 --> 12:47.141
- Oh, no.

12:47.141 --> 12:48.601
- Sure did.

12:48.601 --> 12:51.145
