15:22.004 --> 15:25.383
- Ten, nine, eight,

15:25.383 --> 15:28.678
seven, six, five,

15:28.678 --> 15:32.723
four, three, two,
one.

15:32.723 --> 15:34.350
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines.

15:34.350 --> 15:36.269
Pull your blade out of
the quench.

15:36.269 --> 15:39.188
This first round of competition
is over.

15:39.188 --> 15:41.524
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:41.524 --> 15:43.609
<i>- At this point, the knife's</i>
<i>in the judge's hands.</i>

15:43.609 --> 15:44.694
They're gonna take
a look at it.

15:44.694 --> 15:46.487
They're gonna scrutinize it.

15:46.487 --> 15:48.698
<i>They're all better at making</i>
<i>blades than I am.</i>

15:48.698 --> 15:51.534
So I can't wait to get
their feedback.

15:51.534 --> 15:57.832
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:57.832 --> 16:00.501
- All right, bladesmiths,
what we've got here

16:00.501 --> 16:03.045
is a failure to communicate.

16:03.045 --> 16:04.797
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:04.797 --> 16:08.050
This is an unusual situation
here on "Forged in Fire."

16:08.050 --> 16:11.304
I see two of our knives
on there.

16:11.304 --> 16:13.764
What are they doing?

16:13.764 --> 16:15.850
<i>- I see my blade</i>
<i>and I see Trystan's blade,</i>

16:15.850 --> 16:17.560
<i>and the judges are</i>
<i>mad-dogging us.</i>

16:17.560 --> 16:21.230
And I'm thinking,
"Okay, what's going on here?"

16:21.230 --> 16:22.899
- The judges have evaluated
your work

16:22.899 --> 16:25.359
and believe it or not,
