<i>and then shape it around</i>
<i>the tang.</i>

22:31.642 --> 22:35.396
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:35.396 --> 22:37.731
Ah, come on!

22:37.731 --> 22:39.817
<i>I'm really struggling</i>
<i>with this</i>

22:39.817 --> 22:41.986
and I'm spending way too much
time on it.

22:41.986 --> 22:45.114
I'm trying all these
different methods

22:45.114 --> 22:48.325
that I can think of
that will remove the material,

22:48.325 --> 22:49.994
and nothing's working for me.

22:49.994 --> 22:51.662
[bleep]

22:51.662 --> 22:54.206
- There is not that much time
left on the clock, man.

22:54.206 --> 22:56.667
This is not looking good
for Brian.

22:56.667 --> 22:58.294
- This is unbelievable!

22:58.294 --> 23:00.546
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:00.546 --> 23:02.798
I'm thinking this might be
impossible to finish.

23:05.239 --> 23:05.866
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:05.866 --> 23:07.344
- This is unbelievable.

23:07.344 --> 23:08.846
[sighs]

23:08.846 --> 23:10.806
I'm trying all these
different methods

23:10.806 --> 23:13.809
that I can think of that will
remove the material

23:13.809 --> 23:17.021
on the guard,
and nothing's working for me.

23:17.021 --> 23:20.816
<i>At this point, more than half</i>
<i>of my time's already gone,</i>

23:20.816 --> 23:23.319
and I realize
that I can't spend

23:23.319 --> 23:25.487
any more time on this brass.

23:25.487 --> 23:29.450
- There is a simple fix to what
Brian is doing.

23:29.450 --> 23:32.703
He could have drilled that out
with a larger drill bit

23:32.703 --> 23:34.455
so he could actually fit
the file in there.

23:34.455 --> 23:38.584
And then hammer that brass down
and close up that gap.

23:38.584 --> 23:41.086
- People work with brass on
purpose, I hear.

23:41.086 --> 23:42.963
I just need to scrap it.

23:42.963 --> 23:44.965
For my new guard
I'm gonna use G10

23:44.965 --> 23:47.009
just out of bare necessity.

23:47.009 --> 23:48.385
<i>I'm trying to make up</i>
<i>for lost time,</i>

23:48.385 --> 23:50.512
see if I can get a guard in
place.

23:50.512 --> 23:53.432
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:53.432 --> 23:55.100
- I need to start working on
my pommel.

23:55.100 --> 23:56.852
I want it to be
a teardrop shape.

23:56.852 --> 23:58.562
That would just look really
nice to me.

23:58.562 --> 24:00.481
I think it'd be really
aesthetically pleasing.

24:00.481 --> 24:01.899
- I think what Trystan is doing

24:01.899 --> 24:03.901
is almost hazardous
to the end user.

24:03.901 --> 24:05.653
- That's a lot of pointy bits
on Trystan's knife.

24:05.653 --> 24:07.112
- I mean, it's the last thing

24:07.112 --> 24:08.447
you want in
a survival situation

24:08.447 --> 24:09.657
is to stab yourself.

24:09.657 --> 24:11.241
- [laughing]

24:11.241 --> 24:13.577
- This is a true Hollywood
survival knife.

24:13.577 --> 24:15.037
- Exactly.
- This thing

24:15.037 --> 24:17.164
might only be a prop.

24:17.164 --> 24:19.917
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:19.917 --> 24:22.544
- My goal right now is
to get a handle

24:22.544 --> 24:25.839
that the judge feels
comfortable with.

24:25.839 --> 24:28.008
- Mike's doing a fantastic job,
man.

24:28.008 --> 24:29.593
He's taking his time.

24:29.593 --> 24:32.554
He's really paying attention
to the details.

24:32.554 --> 24:34.598
<i>- I'm gonna put a nice little</i>
<i>finger groove in it.</i>

24:34.598 --> 24:37.893
Contour the insides so it fits
perfect in the judge's hand.

24:37.893 --> 24:40.396
And when he uses it, it's gonna
feel great.

24:40.396 --> 24:42.773
- Wow, that looks sweet.
- Wow.

24:42.773 --> 24:46.318
- You only have ten minutes
remaining.

24:46.318 --> 24:48.821
- Got a guard...ish.

24:48.821 --> 24:52.366
- Guys, I don't think Brian's
gonna make it here.

24:52.366 --> 24:54.535
- I'm gonna turn in a blade,
dang it.

24:54.535 --> 24:57.329
I just struggled with the brass
for an hour and a half.

24:57.329 --> 24:59.123
<i>So for my handle material,</i>

24:59.123 --> 25:00.833
<i>I'm just gonna choose G10.</i>

25:00.833 --> 25:02.418
This is the ugliest thing
I've ever seen.

25:02.418 --> 25:03.877
- Brian's tang is pretty short.

25:03.877 --> 25:05.295
So right now it's
a hidden tang.

25:05.295 --> 25:07.047
- In his mind,
all he's thinking is,

25:07.047 --> 25:08.424
"I gotta finish the blade,
I gotta finish the blade."

25:08.424 --> 25:09.717
No, you don't have
to finish the blade.

25:09.717 --> 25:11.176
You need to finish
the blade within

25:11.176 --> 25:12.761
the parameters we're asking.
- Exactly.

25:12.761 --> 25:14.263
- I still don't have a knife.

25:14.263 --> 25:17.182
- Brian, get to the chopper!

25:17.182 --> 25:19.393
- I'm gonna work as hard
as I've ever worked in my life

25:19.393 --> 25:21.854
to get this done.

25:21.854 --> 25:24.273
It's gonna take a miracle.

25:24.273 --> 25:27.234
- Five, four,

25:27.234 --> 25:29.862
three, two, one.

25:29.862 --> 25:31.864
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines,

25:31.864 --> 25:33.282
drop your tools!

25:33.282 --> 25:35.993
This second round
of competition is over.

25:35.993 --> 25:37.619
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:37.619 --> 25:39.830
- I had to make all kinds
of concessions

25:39.830 --> 25:41.999
to put a handle on the knife.

25:41.999 --> 25:43.792
<i>I'm really proud</i>
<i>of the effort,</i>

25:43.792 --> 25:47.379
but I'm really disappointed
with the finished product.

25:47.379 --> 25:50.215
- All right gentlemen,
welcome to the strength test.

25:50.215 --> 25:51.967
Now everybody knows, in
a Hollywood movie,

25:51.967 --> 25:54.011
there comes a point where
the hero--that's me--

25:54.011 --> 25:56.638
is being chased by a group
of inept villains--

25:56.638 --> 25:58.390
that's them.

25:58.390 --> 26:00.476
Now, the survival knife
has to be capable

26:00.476 --> 26:02.853
of dismantling booby traps.

26:02.853 --> 26:04.438
To test the strength
and overall construction

26:04.438 --> 26:06.648
of your blade, I'll be using
your knife to break

26:06.648 --> 26:08.776
the spikes off
our man-killer over here.

26:08.776 --> 26:10.569
Mike, you're up first.
You ready?

26:10.569 --> 26:12.071
- I'm ready.
- Okay.

26:12.071 --> 26:15.115
<i>[tense music]</i>

26:15.115 --> 26:17.201
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:17.201 --> 26:19.411
<i>- The test I saw earlier,</i>
<i>it just goes to show</i>

26:19.411 --> 26:21.955
<i>that they're gonna have no</i>
<i>mercy on these knives.</i>

26:21.955 --> 26:23.957
So I am a little bit nervous.

26:23.957 --> 26:30.964
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:46.396 --> 26:48.357
- I'd put that in a movie.

26:48.357 --> 26:49.650
[laughing]

26:49.650 --> 26:51.276
It indexes beautifully.

26:51.276 --> 26:54.905
and your finger welds line up
really, really nicely.

26:54.905 --> 26:58.408
Your blade,
there's not a mark on it.

26:58.408 --> 27:00.285
Nicely done.
- Thank you.

27:00.285 --> 27:01.995
- Trystan, you're up.
You ready?

27:01.995 --> 27:04.414
- Yes, sir.

27:04.414 --> 27:06.500
<i>I already know I have</i>
<i>a hard edge,</i>

27:06.500 --> 27:08.460
<i>but these tests are brutal</i>
<i>and they really can</i>

27:08.460 --> 27:10.629
bring out all the flaws in
anyone's blade.

27:10.629 --> 27:13.048
So it's still anyone's game.

27:13.048 --> 27:20.097
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:34.194 --> 27:36.113
- Nice!

27:37.155 --> 27:38.657
- All right, Trystan.

27:38.657 --> 27:41.243
You've got, right here,
just a small roll

27:41.243 --> 27:42.786
that I can feel.

27:42.786 --> 27:45.455
There's another glint down here
on the edge,

27:45.455 --> 27:49.084
but biggest issue is
that pommel.

27:49.084 --> 27:50.502
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:50.502 --> 27:51.879
This kicked over to the side

27:51.879 --> 27:54.590
because it was whacking into
my wrist.

27:54.590 --> 27:56.842
Designing a knife,
having a spike come this way

27:56.842 --> 27:59.261
towards your hand,
really never a good idea.

27:59.261 --> 28:03.181
- Thank you, I'll remember
that for the rest of my life.

28:03.181 --> 28:05.267
- All right, Brian.
You ready for this?

28:05.267 --> 28:07.519
- I'm ready.
I don't know if the knife is.

28:07.519 --> 28:09.521
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:09.521 --> 28:12.357
<i>Seeing this log with all</i>
<i>the spikes sticking out of it,</i>

28:12.357 --> 28:13.775
<i>it reminds me of the movies.</i>
<i>You know,</i>

28:13.775 --> 28:15.527
<i>"Predator," "Rambo."</i>

28:15.527 --> 28:16.778
It's very exciting
to see the test

28:16.778 --> 28:19.615
and watch David
do what he does.

28:19.615 --> 28:24.161
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:24.161 --> 28:26.079
- It's...

28:26.079 --> 28:27.814
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:31.835 --> 28:33.670
- It's...

28:33.670 --> 28:36.214
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:36.214 --> 28:37.674
<i>- David picks up my knife,</i>

28:37.674 --> 28:39.301
<i>he's taking a look</i>
<i>at it and trying</i>

28:39.301 --> 28:40.886
<i>to figure out where</i>
<i>to put the lanyard,</i>

28:40.886 --> 28:43.013
<i>and he puts it back in</i>
<i>his pocket.</i>

28:43.013 --> 28:45.515
This isn't a good sign.

28:45.515 --> 28:48.518
- Brian, I really appreciate
a good work-around,

28:48.518 --> 28:51.355
and you're really shooting
for one here

28:51.355 --> 28:52.731
and you worked really hard.

28:52.731 --> 28:55.734
That last 30 minutes,
you pushed hard,

28:55.734 --> 28:58.320
but this isn't a through-tang
with a pommel.

28:58.320 --> 29:01.323
This is a hidden tang
and a frame handle.

29:01.323 --> 29:03.075
- Understood.

29:03.075 --> 29:06.620
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:06.620 --> 29:10.207
- Brian, your blade failed
to meet round two parameters.

29:10.207 --> 29:12.501
For that reason, I have to ask
you to please leave The Forge.

29:12.501 --> 29:14.002
- Thank you.

29:14.002 --> 29:18.632
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:18.632 --> 29:20.634
<i>I completely agree with</i>
<i>the judges</i>

29:20.634 --> 29:22.511
and I understand why
I'm going home,

29:22.511 --> 29:25.097
<i>but my family,</i>
<i>we don't throw in the towel.</i>

29:25.097 --> 29:27.182
<i>We always keep going.</i>

29:27.182 --> 29:30.519
When I get home I'm going
to hug my kiddos,

29:30.519 --> 29:33.939
kiss my wife,
probably take a sweet nap,

29:33.939 --> 29:35.732
<i>and then get back to forging.</i>

29:35.732 --> 29:37.818
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:37.818 --> 29:39.987
- Trystan, Mike,
congratulations.

29:39.987 --> 29:42.489
You've landed in the third
round of this competition.

29:42.489 --> 29:44.116
When you showed up here
we asked you

29:44.116 --> 29:46.868
to make survival knives
inspired by John Rambo

29:46.868 --> 29:49.788
in the film "First Blood"
from 1982.

29:49.788 --> 29:52.124
Now we're sending you back
to your home forges

29:52.124 --> 29:53.875
to re-create an iconic weapon
from history

29:53.875 --> 29:55.585
and from Hollywood.

29:55.585 --> 29:56.920
That weapon is...

29:56.920 --> 29:59.214
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

29:59.214 --> 30:01.091
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:01.091 --> 30:03.844
- The Hattori Hanzo
1,000-layer katana.

30:03.844 --> 30:07.305
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:07.305 --> 30:09.057
- Whoa.

30:09.057 --> 30:11.351
<i>- Born in 16th-century Japan,</i>
<i>Hattori Hanzo,</i>

30:11.351 --> 30:13.270
<i>also known as Devil Hanzo,</i>

30:13.270 --> 30:16.481
<i>was perhaps the most legendary</i>
<i>samurai to ever live.</i>

30:16.481 --> 30:18.316
<i>Almost 400 years later</i>

30:18.316 --> 30:21.111
<i>in the 2003 Tarantino cult</i>
<i>classic, "Kill Bill,"</i>

30:21.111 --> 30:23.989
<i>Hattori Hanzo was re-imagined</i>
<i>as the modern day bladesmith</i>

30:23.989 --> 30:28.160
<i>who creates a katana so</i>
<i>fine it would cut God.</i>

30:28.160 --> 30:30.996
<i>In reality, the katana is</i>
<i>the majestic symbol</i>

30:30.996 --> 30:33.915
<i>of the ancient warrior</i>
<i>samurai, featuring a simple</i>

30:33.915 --> 30:35.876
<i>but elegant single-edged blade</i>

30:35.876 --> 30:39.129
<i>designed for precise cuts</i>
<i>and lightning-fast thrusts.</i>

30:39.129 --> 30:41.673
<i>The dazzling Damascus flare</i>
<i>produces not only</i>

30:41.673 --> 30:44.217
<i>a beautiful piece of steel,</i>
<i>but an incredibly sharp</i>

30:44.217 --> 30:46.762
<i>and deadly cutting edge.</i>

30:46.762 --> 30:49.181
The blade parameters are
as follows.

30:49.181 --> 30:51.641
You must include a habaki,
a tsuba guard,

30:51.641 --> 30:53.977
and tsuka handle between
11 and 12 inches,

30:53.977 --> 30:55.854
and your handle must be
wrapped.

30:55.854 --> 30:58.356
Now, 300 layers of Damascus
steel is considered

30:58.356 --> 31:00.233
a major bladesmithing
accomplishment.

31:00.233 --> 31:04.154
However, this blade must
be 1,000 layers, gentlemen.

31:04.154 --> 31:06.156
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:06.156 --> 31:08.366
<i>- The biggest Damascus build</i>
<i>that I've ever made</i>

31:08.366 --> 31:09.701
<i>is 20 layers.</i>

31:09.701 --> 31:12.621
This thing is insane.

31:12.621 --> 31:14.331
- You will have five days
at your home forges

31:14.331 --> 31:16.208
to accomplish this challenge.

31:16.208 --> 31:18.668
After five days you will return
and present your blades

31:18.668 --> 31:21.046
to our panel of expert judges,
and only after

31:21.046 --> 31:23.048
they have thoroughly tested
them will they declare

31:23.048 --> 31:24.716
one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion

31:24.716 --> 31:26.843
who walks out of here with
a check for 10 grand.

31:26.843 --> 31:29.137
Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in five days.

31:29.137 --> 31:30.597
- [sighs]
- Let's do this, man.

31:30.597 --> 31:31.681
- All right.

31:31.681 --> 31:34.226
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:34.226 --> 31:36.603
- I'm excited to be back here
in Trussville, Alabama.

31:36.603 --> 31:39.606
Getting ready to start
the Hattori Hanzo katana.

31:39.606 --> 31:41.108
Here we go.

31:41.108 --> 31:42.526
<i>Even though I've made</i>
<i>Damascus before,</i>

31:42.526 --> 31:44.653
I've never made 1,000 layers.

31:44.653 --> 31:46.488
<i>It's gonna be</i>
<i>incredibly difficult.</i>

31:46.488 --> 31:48.281
<i>I really need to this right</i>
<i>the first time.</i>

31:48.281 --> 31:50.200
Kay, that's my initial weld.

31:50.200 --> 31:53.120
If I mess this up, I'm done.

31:53.120 --> 31:56.623
I'd like to have at least half
of my billet forged up today.

31:56.623 --> 31:58.834
<i>Maybe 500, maybe more layers.</i>

31:58.834 --> 32:01.545
This is where
the fun stuff begins.

32:01.545 --> 32:04.339
Grinding with a grinder.

32:04.339 --> 32:08.009
So now I have my billet divided
into five pieces

32:08.009 --> 32:11.555
and I will restack these
and weld them together.

32:11.555 --> 32:15.142
<i>I am truly blessed to have</i>
<i>a press and a power hammer.</i>

32:15.142 --> 32:18.645
By hand, this is very
difficult and slow.

32:18.645 --> 32:20.147
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:20.147 --> 32:22.023
So now I'm at 620 layers.

32:22.023 --> 32:23.650
<i>All I have to do is cut</i>
<i>it in half,</i>

32:23.650 --> 32:25.152
weld those two halves
together,

32:25.152 --> 32:27.487
and now I have 1,240 layers.

32:27.487 --> 32:29.364
<i>It's been</i>
<i>a very successful day.</i>

32:29.364 --> 32:31.741
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:31.741 --> 32:34.953
<i>- It's day one, and I'm making</i>
<i>a Hattori Hanzo style katana,</i>

32:34.953 --> 32:37.372
and that's gonna be tough on me
just because I've never

32:37.372 --> 32:39.124
<i>done something</i>
<i>this big before.</i>

32:39.124 --> 32:41.877
I'm gonna start by working on
my 1,000-layer Damascus.

32:41.877 --> 32:45.589
So the weld looks like
it held together really well.

32:45.589 --> 32:48.175
Good start. Good start.

32:48.175 --> 32:49.759
<i>The problem with</i>
<i>the 1,000-layer Damascus</i>

32:49.759 --> 32:52.179
is that there are 999 spots in
the billet

32:52.179 --> 32:54.055
that's possibly going
to go wrong.

32:54.055 --> 32:57.434
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:57.434 --> 32:59.227
<i>If I had power tools,</i>
<i>I feel like I could have</i>

32:59.227 --> 33:00.770
<i>pumped this out a lot faster.</i>

33:00.770 --> 33:02.272
This is taking forever.

33:02.272 --> 33:03.773
<i>I thought that I was</i>
<i>gonna be able</i>

33:03.773 --> 33:05.483
<i>to get 1,000 layers done</i>
<i>in one day.</i>

33:05.483 --> 33:08.069
I've got 42 layers.

33:08.069 --> 33:09.154
Whoo.

33:09.154 --> 33:10.739
<i>But being at 42 layers</i>

33:10.739 --> 33:12.532
<i>is still only</i>
<i>three forge welds away</i>

33:12.532 --> 33:14.242
from being at over a thousand.

33:14.242 --> 33:16.328
[laughs]

33:16.328 --> 33:18.079
<i>- Today,</i>
<i>I actually feel good</i>

33:18.079 --> 33:20.624
because I have more than
the required number of layers.

33:20.624 --> 33:22.709
<i>I'm pretty happy</i>
<i>with the profile.</i>

33:22.709 --> 33:25.754
<i>So now I can go into</i>
<i>my heat treat.</i>

33:25.754 --> 33:28.715
I don't typically do
blades this long.

33:28.715 --> 33:31.218
<i>So what I'm gonna do</i>
<i>is put two forges together</i>

33:31.218 --> 33:33.887
<i>to create an even heat</i>
<i>throughout this blade</i>

33:33.887 --> 33:35.639
<i>as I get ready to harden it.</i>

33:35.639 --> 33:39.184
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:39.184 --> 33:40.685
I pull the blade out.

33:40.685 --> 33:42.646
Kay, I'm starting to get
a warp in it.

33:42.646 --> 33:44.439
<i>Part of me wants to freak out.</i>

33:44.439 --> 33:46.441
<i>By the time the blade</i>
<i>is cooled down a lot</i>

33:46.441 --> 33:49.986
I see that it's got
essentially two bends in it.

33:49.986 --> 33:51.363
<i>I quenched a second time.</i>

33:51.363 --> 33:52.948
The blade has a slight warp
in it,

33:52.948 --> 33:54.658
<i>but it's something</i>
<i>that can be ground out.</i>

33:54.658 --> 33:56.660
So I'm really happy right now.

33:56.660 --> 33:58.036
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:58.036 --> 33:59.371
<i>- Yesterday I was able</i>

33:59.371 --> 34:00.872
<i>to forge my 1,000-layer</i>
<i>billet,</i>

34:00.872 --> 34:02.791
but it's looking lean.

34:02.791 --> 34:04.668
<i>So in order to get the weight</i>
<i>that I need</i>

34:04.668 --> 34:06.753
<i>to be able to get the sword</i>
<i>to length,</i>

34:06.753 --> 34:08.755
I've forge welded
mild steel to the back

34:08.755 --> 34:10.340
<i>and the sides of it.</i>

34:10.340 --> 34:12.092
<i>I think it'll make</i>
<i>the blade stronger.</i>

34:12.092 --> 34:13.843
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:13.843 --> 34:15.929
<i>I'm doing the heat treat</i>
<i>on my katana with charcoal</i>

34:15.929 --> 34:18.515
<i>and I'm pretty nervous.</i>

34:18.515 --> 34:20.558
This is the make
or break moment.

34:20.558 --> 34:22.894
The quench is insanely critical

34:22.894 --> 34:24.896
<i>for the completion</i>
<i>of this piece.</i>

34:24.896 --> 34:28.191
<i>This blade needs to be perfect</i>
<i>from here on.</i>

34:28.191 --> 34:29.567
<i>If anything goes wrong,</i>

34:29.567 --> 34:31.194
I won't be able to finish
this piece.

34:31.194 --> 34:34.420
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:38.743 --> 34:40.161
<i>I'm pretty nervous.</i>

34:40.161 --> 34:42.080
If there's a warp
that goes the wrong way,

34:42.080 --> 34:43.623
<i>I don't know if there's any</i>
<i>straightening out</i>

34:43.623 --> 34:44.958
<i>with this type of steel.</i>

34:44.958 --> 34:49.713
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:49.713 --> 34:52.507
Straight.

34:52.507 --> 34:54.384
[laughs]

34:54.384 --> 34:55.927
Whoo!

34:55.927 --> 34:57.804
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:57.804 --> 35:00.056
- So today I have
my blade ready.

35:00.056 --> 35:02.684
<i>Now I just need to start</i>
<i>making all the handle parts.</i>

35:02.684 --> 35:06.313
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:06.313 --> 35:10.442
I have the habaki fitting up
nicely.

35:10.442 --> 35:13.945
The tsuba is right here.

35:13.945 --> 35:15.989
<i>This handle has to be tight.</i>

35:15.989 --> 35:17.949
This sword is gonna be beat up.

35:17.949 --> 35:21.202
<i>So now it's gonna be wrapped</i>
<i>in sting ray skin</i>

35:21.202 --> 35:23.622
<i>and ito cord.</i>

35:23.622 --> 35:24.789
I'm pretty happy with it.

35:24.789 --> 35:26.249
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:26.249 --> 35:27.917
<i>- On the last day,</i>
<i>the first thing</i>

35:27.917 --> 35:30.253
<i>I want to get done</i>
<i>is carve out the tsuka.</i>

35:30.253 --> 35:32.005
I'm using a piece of walnut.

35:32.005 --> 35:33.882
<i>It's just a really</i>
<i>strong wood.</i>

35:33.882 --> 35:36.217
<i>Ah, it's starting to look</i>
<i>really nice.</i>

35:36.217 --> 35:37.886
<i>After I finish carving it out</i>

35:37.886 --> 35:40.430
I'm gonna put some ray skin
on the sides of it

35:40.430 --> 35:42.057
and give it a wrap.

35:42.057 --> 35:44.517
<i>My biggest deviation from</i>
<i>the tradition is</i>

35:44.517 --> 35:46.561
I'm using shoelaces
for my wrap.

35:46.561 --> 35:48.063
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:48.063 --> 35:50.148
<i>It just feels the nicest,</i>

35:50.148 --> 35:53.068
but they're shoelaces.

35:53.068 --> 35:55.528
Yeah, everything feels
really together.

35:55.528 --> 35:56.988
Let's go hit things.

35:56.988 --> 36:00.450
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:00.450 --> 36:03.453
<i>[tense music]</i>

36:03.453 --> 36:05.872
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:05.872 --> 36:07.916
- Trystan, Mike, welcome back
to The Forge.

36:07.916 --> 36:10.794
You two badass bladesmiths have
had five days

36:10.794 --> 36:14.089
at your home forges to work on
our salute to Hollywood,

36:14.089 --> 36:17.842
Hattori Hanzo
1,000 layer katanas.

36:17.842 --> 36:19.511
Trystan, how'd it go for you?

36:19.511 --> 36:21.638
- Forging my 1,000 layer
Hattori Hanzo sword

36:21.638 --> 36:23.306
was a challenge.

36:23.306 --> 36:26.935
<i>The steel that I used</i>
<i>is 5160 W2 Damascus</i>

36:26.935 --> 36:29.062
<i>with a soft steel jacket,</i>

36:29.062 --> 36:31.106
<i>and mokume-gane fittings.</i>

36:31.106 --> 36:32.399
- All right.

36:32.399 --> 36:33.942
Mike, how'd it go for you?

36:33.942 --> 36:35.694
- It was an awesome experience,

36:35.694 --> 36:37.570
<i>but also a huge challenge.</i>

36:37.570 --> 36:40.073
<i>Started off with 1080</i>
<i>and 15N20,</i>

36:40.073 --> 36:42.742
<i>1,240 layers of Damascus</i>
<i>steel,</i>

36:42.742 --> 36:44.953
wrapping with stingray skin.

36:44.953 --> 36:46.746
- All right, bladesmiths.

36:46.746 --> 36:48.957
There will be a strength test,
a sharpness test,

36:48.957 --> 36:52.752
and up first, Doug Marcaida's
kill test.

36:52.752 --> 36:54.504
Doug.

36:54.504 --> 36:56.256
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:56.256 --> 36:59.134
- Bladesmiths,
a Hanzo's katana's first duty

36:59.134 --> 37:00.760
is to kill.

37:00.760 --> 37:02.303
To find out what kind of
lethal damage

37:02.303 --> 37:04.305
your weapon will do,
I will take your katana

37:04.305 --> 37:07.183
and deliver killing blows
on this ballistics dummy.

37:07.183 --> 37:08.476
All right, Mike,
you're up first.

37:08.476 --> 37:09.644
Are you ready?
- Yes, sir.

37:09.644 --> 37:11.187
- Let's do this.

37:11.187 --> 37:13.690
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

37:13.690 --> 37:15.442
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:15.442 --> 37:18.862
- All the years up until now
has gone into this blade.

37:18.862 --> 37:22.741
It's not just a five-day blade,
it's a fifteen-year blade.

37:22.741 --> 37:29.789
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:38.131 --> 37:41.676
[grunting]

37:41.676 --> 37:44.053
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:44.053 --> 37:45.764
[grunts]

37:45.764 --> 37:50.018
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:50.018 --> 37:51.853
- Yes.

37:51.853 --> 37:55.482
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:55.482 --> 37:58.777
- Mike, your edge
is razor sharp.

37:58.777 --> 38:02.030
But more importantly,
there's bone on your edge,

38:02.030 --> 38:04.866
but your edge did not roll,
did not chip,

38:04.866 --> 38:08.328
and your blade stayed true.

38:08.328 --> 38:10.789
Overall, sir, your blade...

38:10.789 --> 38:11.831
[blood squelches]

38:11.831 --> 38:12.957
Will kill.

38:12.957 --> 38:14.292
- Thank you.

38:14.292 --> 38:16.252
- Trystan, you ready?
- Yes, sir.

38:16.252 --> 38:17.962
- Let's do this.

38:17.962 --> 38:20.590
- I'm really hoping
that I don't see any damage

38:20.590 --> 38:21.716
happening to my blade.

38:21.716 --> 38:23.176
<i>I know that I have a hard edge</i>

38:23.176 --> 38:24.677
and I know I have
a soft steel spine

38:24.677 --> 38:26.012
to support that hard edge,

38:26.012 --> 38:28.264
and it shouldn't be moving
anywhere.

38:28.264 --> 38:34.896
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:34.896 --> 38:36.648
- [grunts]

38:46.407 --> 38:47.784
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:47.784 --> 38:49.619
Hah!

38:49.619 --> 38:56.417
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:56.417 --> 38:58.002
- [quietly] Oh, my gosh.

39:07.095 --> 39:08.513
- All right, Trystan,

39:08.513 --> 39:10.849
the balance of your blade
is very good.

39:10.849 --> 39:15.019
It's light, it's fast,
it's easily maneuverable.

39:15.019 --> 39:18.606
But when steel meets the skull

39:18.606 --> 39:20.316
there was some problems.

39:20.316 --> 39:23.111
Your blade took a serious bend.

39:23.111 --> 39:25.780
Also on the edge right here,

39:25.780 --> 39:27.532
you took some chipping.

39:27.532 --> 39:30.201
But overall,
looking at the dummy,

39:30.201 --> 39:33.496
I think your weapon
will definitely kill.

39:33.496 --> 39:35.164
- Thank you.

39:35.164 --> 39:37.166
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:37.166 --> 39:40.545
- Gentlemen, the second duty
of a Hanzo katana

39:40.545 --> 39:42.380
is that it has to be sharp.

39:42.380 --> 39:43.798
It is said
that the Hanzo katana

39:43.798 --> 39:46.801
is as sharp as
1,000 razor blades.

39:46.801 --> 39:49.846
A sharp blade should cut clean
through tatami mats.

39:49.846 --> 39:53.808
A dull blade will crush, bend,
or get hung up.

39:53.808 --> 39:58.104
A dull blade is not
a Hanzo katana.

39:58.104 --> 39:59.439
Mike, you're up first.

39:59.439 --> 40:01.357
You ready for this?
- Yes, I'm ready.

40:01.357 --> 40:02.901
- Let's do this.

40:02.901 --> 40:04.861
<i>- Going into this,</i>
<i>I'm a little bit nervous</i>

40:04.861 --> 40:07.447
because I know that I went
though a lot of bone

40:07.447 --> 40:09.741
and so, probably the edge
isn't there

40:09.741 --> 40:12.744
that was there when it started.

40:12.744 --> 40:15.586
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:28.134 --> 40:30.803
<i>[grunt]</i>

40:30.803 --> 40:32.847
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:32.847 --> 40:34.349
- [inhales]

40:34.349 --> 40:36.309
Your blade, sir, is sharp.

40:36.309 --> 40:37.810
It cut cleanly through
the thickest

40:37.810 --> 40:40.480
of our tatami mats,
but on the backhand slice,

40:40.480 --> 40:42.357
it did not cut completely
though.

40:42.357 --> 40:45.610
Overall, sir,
your sword will cut.

40:45.610 --> 40:46.861
- Thank you.

40:46.861 --> 40:48.404
- Trystan, your turn.
You ready?

40:48.404 --> 40:50.365
- Ready as I'll ever be, sir.
- Let's do this.

40:50.365 --> 40:52.825
- If one more thing goes wrong
with my katana

40:52.825 --> 40:55.119
<i>I'm definitely gonna be</i>
<i>going home.</i>

40:55.119 --> 40:59.624
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:59.624 --> 41:03.252
- [grunting]

41:03.252 --> 41:04.921
[grunts]

41:04.921 --> 41:09.050
[grunting]

41:09.050 --> 41:12.428
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:12.428 --> 41:14.138
- [sighs]

41:14.138 --> 41:18.476
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:18.476 --> 41:21.688
- Well, Trystan,
your edge is sharp.

41:21.688 --> 41:23.648
It can cut through tatami mats.

41:23.648 --> 41:27.151
My concern is the strength
of your blade.

41:27.151 --> 41:29.153
It picked up another bend.

41:29.153 --> 41:30.947
Now you have two bends on
your blade.

41:30.947 --> 41:33.366
Especially right here, close
to the guard.

41:33.366 --> 41:35.326
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:35.326 --> 41:37.328
- Trystan, this Hollywood
competition

41:37.328 --> 41:39.664
has been exciting and dramatic.

41:39.664 --> 41:43.167
You've been at the epicenter
of all of that drama.

41:43.167 --> 41:46.337
Nobody is questioning
the strength of your character.

41:46.337 --> 41:48.548
However, the strength
of your blade

41:48.548 --> 41:51.426
is such that we can no longer
continue to test it.

41:51.426 --> 41:54.887
For that reason I have to ask
you to please leave The Forge.

41:54.887 --> 41:56.889
- Yes, sir.
- Good job.

41:56.889 --> 41:59.142
- Guess I just couldn't
slip through.

41:59.142 --> 42:01.436
[laughs]

42:01.436 --> 42:03.021
<i>Objectively speaking,</i>

42:03.021 --> 42:04.564
one of the blades
is better than the other,

42:04.564 --> 42:06.065
and it's clear to see,

42:06.065 --> 42:07.567
<i>because one of them</i>
<i>is straight.</i>

42:07.567 --> 42:09.235
I may not be
"Forged in Fire" champion,

42:09.235 --> 42:11.029
but second place isn't bad
for somebody

42:11.029 --> 42:14.157
<i>who's never done this before.</i>
<i>[chuckles]</i>

42:14.157 --> 42:16.826
- Mike, you were an unstoppable
force in this competition

42:16.826 --> 42:19.662
and your Hattori Hanzo
1,000 layer katana

42:19.662 --> 42:21.831
is absolutely deadly,

42:21.831 --> 42:24.417
earning you the title of
"Forged in Fire" champion

42:24.417 --> 42:27.170
and a check for 10 grand.
Good job.

42:27.170 --> 42:29.672
- I came here to show myself

42:29.672 --> 42:32.592
that I can make a blade worthy
of undergoing

42:32.592 --> 42:34.385
<i>this type of punishment.</i>

42:34.385 --> 42:36.846
I am "Forged in Fire" champion

42:36.846 --> 42:39.307
and it feels awesome.

42:39.307 --> 42:46.355
<i>♪ ♪</i>
